# Dependency Inversion Skill

## Purpose
Guide an AI agent through applying the Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) to keep the application core independent of infrastructure choices.

## Sections to Generate

### When to Use This Skill
Refactoring a direct dependency into an injected one, introducing a new external dependency, splitting a module to break cyclic imports, or fixing test setup that requires real infrastructure.

### The Principle
- High-level modules (use cases, domain) MUST NOT depend on low-level modules (DB, frameworks)
- Both should depend on **abstractions** (ports/interfaces)
- Abstractions should NOT depend on details; details depend on abstractions

### Practical Application
- Define the abstraction (port) **in the core**, alongside the use case that needs it
- Implement the abstraction (adapter) in infrastructure
- Inject at the composition root via constructor injection

### Common Refactor Pattern
1. Identify the offending direct dependency in the core
2. Extract its usage into a port interface owned by the core
3. Move the implementation to an adapter package
4. Update the use case to accept the port via constructor
5. Wire the adapter at composition root

### Testability Win
Once DIP is applied, the use case can be unit-tested with a fake/stub implementing the port — no DB, no HTTP, no real time, no flakiness.

### Anti-patterns to Avoid
- "Service locator" patterns that hide dependencies
- Static factories or singletons in the core that resolve to concrete implementations
- Generic `IRepository` over specific domain ports — abstraction has to be **about something**, not "everything"

### Verification
DIP correctly applied: the core module has zero imports of `database/sql`, `net/http`, or framework packages; tests for use cases run with no external infrastructure.
